WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.480 --> 00:00:05.280
Right in the center of the South American&nbsp;
continent, encircled by mountain ranges and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:05.280 --> 00:00:10.800
highlands on all sides, one of the most remarkable&nbsp;
natural spectacles is undergoing a relentless&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:10.800 --> 00:00:17.040
natural cycle of devastation and rebirth every&nbsp;
year. During the wet season between November and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:17.040 --> 00:00:22.480
March, the Paraguay River and its tributaries&nbsp;
are rushing down the Brazilian Highlands,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:22.480 --> 00:00:27.120
only to be stopped in their tracks by an&nbsp;
enormous basin that slopes at barely 1 to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:27.120 --> 00:00:33.120
2 centimeters per kilometer. Unable to drain&nbsp;
away, the river channels fill beyond capacity,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:33.120 --> 00:00:38.880
overflowing into the vast savannah to create the&nbsp;
world's largest seasonal floodplain and one of the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:38.880 --> 00:00:45.840
most unique biomes on earth. This is the Pantanal.
To fully understand the mechanics of this complex&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:45.840 --> 00:00:50.880
hydrological system, in this video we will&nbsp;
explore the unique annual water cycle with its&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:50.880 --> 00:00:56.800
consequences on the wildlife and which challenges&nbsp;
arise, when humans are trying to built a livelihood&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:56.800 --> 00:01:01.920
in such an environment.
Phase 1) The wet season&nbsp;

00:01:01.920 --> 00:01:07.120
With the beginning of the wet season in November,&nbsp;
increased rainfall over the Brazilian Highlands&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:07.120 --> 00:01:13.600
and the Chapada dos Guimarães set off a pulse&nbsp;
which changes the downstream ecology for months to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:13.600 --> 00:01:20.240
come. When precipitation in the plateaus increases&nbsp;
10-fold compared to the dry winters, the Paraguay&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:20.240 --> 00:01:26.400
River and its many tributaries are tirelessly&nbsp;
sending forth the waters into the Pantanal Basin,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:26.400 --> 00:01:31.200
but once the slopes fade and hundreds of&nbsp;
kilometers of leveled savannah open up at the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:31.200 --> 00:01:37.120
foothills, the waters seemingly come to a halt.
Over the next months, with not enough pressure&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:37.120 --> 00:01:41.520
to be pushed along, the water levels in&nbsp;
the river channels rise progressively,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:41.520 --> 00:01:48.160
until the river banks breach and the waters expand&nbsp;
laterally across the whole basin. Every depression&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:48.160 --> 00:01:55.200
of the 150.000 square kilometer Pantanal, roughly&nbsp;
the size of Georgia or Illinois, slowly but surely&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:55.200 --> 00:02:02.080
gets submerged, and pretty much every aspect of&nbsp;
the habitat undergoes drastic changes. Isolated&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:02.080 --> 00:02:10.400
lakes are reconnected to the larger hydro-system,&nbsp;
meadows become swamps, hills become islands, and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:10.400 --> 00:02:17.200
the new sediments and nutrients from the hillsides&nbsp;
ignite an explosion of life. Due to the shallow&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:17.200 --> 00:02:22.640
gradient and vast distances, there is actually a&nbsp;
significant lag between the precipitation in the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:22.640 --> 00:02:28.080
Brazilian Highlands, and the eventual rise of&nbsp;
river levels in the Pantanal. And even within&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:28.080 --> 00:02:34.800
the Pantanal itself, the pulse of precipitation&nbsp;
impacts the regions at vastly different times.&nbsp;

00:02:34.800 --> 00:02:40.000
While the northern regions experience increasing&nbsp;
water levels just 1-2 months after the start of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:40.000 --> 00:02:44.880
the wet season in November, the most southern&nbsp;
areas on the border with Paraguay are virtually&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:44.880 --> 00:02:51.440
unchanged until March of the following year.
Phase 2) Peak Flooding&nbsp;

00:02:51.440 --> 00:02:55.120
Despite the precipitation in the&nbsp;
surrounding highlands slowing down again,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:55.120 --> 00:03:00.800
the waters across the whole of the Pantanal are&nbsp;
still rising. The residence time of most water&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:00.800 --> 00:03:07.280
in the system is roughly 5 to 6 months, so peak&nbsp;
flooding across the system will occur at vastly&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:07.280 --> 00:03:12.960
different times. Around May, however, when the&nbsp;
northern sections slowly start draining again,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:12.960 --> 00:03:18.400
the center reaches its peak flood levels&nbsp;
and the water is still rising in the south,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:18.400 --> 00:03:25.040
a total of 80% of the Pantanal is submerged under&nbsp;
a thick blanket of muddy waters. Water levels&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:25.040 --> 00:03:31.280
range from 0.5 to 5 meters in depth, depending&nbsp;
on the local topography and what once started&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:31.280 --> 00:03:37.120
off as countless isolated lagoons, rivers and&nbsp;
lakes has now become the largest interconnected&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:37.120 --> 00:03:42.320
temporary wetlands system in the world.
The stagnant waters and lukewarm temperatures&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:42.320 --> 00:03:50.480
between 25 and 30°C result in the rapid expansion&nbsp;
of Water Hyacinth across the open water zones,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:50.480 --> 00:03:55.600
waterbirds start nesting in the flooded&nbsp;
shallow grass land and fish spawn populates&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:55.600 --> 00:04:02.640
every nook and cranny of the new habitat.
Formerly dry forests become a unique arboreal&nbsp;habitat

00:04:02.640 --> 00:04:06.960
and what formerly were hills, have now become&nbsp;
narrow corridors for terrestrial animals&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:06.960 --> 00:04:12.480
to traverse the completely new landscape.
Virtually every corner of the Pantanal has been&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:12.480 --> 00:04:18.800
reinvented and the advantage shifts decisively&nbsp;
to fish and amphibians who have plenty of food,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:18.800 --> 00:04:24.720
oxygen and shelter. This paradise on earth doesn’t&nbsp;
last forever though and just a few weeks after&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:24.720 --> 00:04:31.360
reaching the peak, the waters start receding&nbsp;
and this new habitat slowly diminishes again.&nbsp;

00:04:31.360 --> 00:04:35.920
Phase 3) Receding waters
As the rainfall dries up in the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:35.920 --> 00:04:41.920
highlands, the lush growth period in the Pantanal&nbsp;
Wetlands slowly comes to an end, and Brazil's apex&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:41.920 --> 00:04:47.040
predators enter their season of abundance.
During the retreat, previously submerged&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:47.040 --> 00:04:52.400
channels called Corixos are emerging again,&nbsp;
and the first mudflats start dissecting the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:52.400 --> 00:04:57.840
continuous watersurface from before. At peak&nbsp;
velocity, the waters in the Pantanal can recede&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:57.840 --> 00:05:04.640
with over 10cm per day, orchestrating a precisely&nbsp;
timed choreography as the land gradually emerges&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:04.640 --> 00:05:11.280
again. After 5 weeks, the sea has fractured into&nbsp;
larger lakes, after 10 weeks, only channels,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:11.280 --> 00:05:17.440
lagoons and depressions hold on to their water,&nbsp;
and after 15 weeks, nearly all freeflowing water&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:17.440 --> 00:05:22.800
outside of the deepest lagoons and permanent&nbsp;
rivers has either refilled the aquifers,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:22.800 --> 00:05:28.720
returned to the main stem of the Paraguay&nbsp;
river or evaporated, leaving behind salt pans.&nbsp;

00:05:28.720 --> 00:05:34.160
The sudden isolation of thousands of small&nbsp;
lagoons across the Pantanal now create a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:34.160 --> 00:05:39.920
challenging environment for the aquatic species&nbsp;
which found themselves in these small pools, with&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:39.920 --> 00:05:46.640
temperatures rising, oxygen levels sinking and pH&nbsp;
levels drastically fluctuating on a daily basis.&nbsp;

00:05:46.640 --> 00:05:53.840
By September, the water coverage declined from 80%&nbsp;
to a mere 20%, locking in most aquatic life in the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:53.840 --> 00:05:59.760
ever smaller pools, which completely reshuffles&nbsp;
the food chain. Storks, Herons and Eagles&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:59.760 --> 00:06:06.000
now migrate from pool to pool, joining otters,&nbsp;
caimans and foxes in their feast on helpless fish.&nbsp;

00:06:06.000 --> 00:06:11.200
Even the jaguar joins in, terrorizing the&nbsp;
rest of the fauna as everyone prepares for&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:11.200 --> 00:06:17.440
the final phase of the annual cycle.
Phase 4) Survival of the fittest&nbsp;

00:06:17.440 --> 00:06:22.640
By the end of September, precipitation in&nbsp;
central Brazil has reached its low point,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:22.640 --> 00:06:28.400
and the climate of the Pantanal starts resembling&nbsp;
that of a desert. Heat waves regularly surpass&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:28.400 --> 00:06:36.160
the 40°C mark, relative humidity plummets, and&nbsp;
the sun is scorching the earth relentlessly.&nbsp;

00:06:36.160 --> 00:06:41.520
For the following two months, only the&nbsp;
deepest ponds will retain any water,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:41.520 --> 00:06:48.400
the exposed grass starts to wither away, and the&nbsp;
sandy earth starts cracking up in the dry heat.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:48.400 --> 00:06:54.240
Most of the vegetation is becoming dormant and&nbsp;
relying on their root network to stay alive,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:54.240 --> 00:06:59.120
just waiting for the rain to return.
Overall, life slows down drastically&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:59.120 --> 00:07:04.640
in the Pantanal and nature's dangers are&nbsp;lurking
everywhere. The brittle straw that once&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:04.640 --> 00:07:10.720
was the lush submerged meadow has now become&nbsp;
the kindling for regular bush fires and in the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:10.720 --> 00:07:16.240
few remaining water sources, now covering only&nbsp;
15% of the Pantanal, ammonia is building up,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:16.240 --> 00:07:23.120
while toxic cyanobacteria are spreading fast.&nbsp;
Aquatic habitats have become a true hunger game&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:23.120 --> 00:07:28.480
where the remaining species are fighting for survival.
The ones that are able to roam the savannah&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:28.480 --> 00:07:32.960
seek refuge in the gallery forests&nbsp;
surrounding the permanent streams,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:32.960 --> 00:07:38.240
trying to persevere until the next rainfall.
Just before the return of the rain in the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:38.240 --> 00:07:43.280
beginning of November, the Pantanal is but a&nbsp;
shadow of itself from just a few months ago,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:43.280 --> 00:07:46.080
but with cooling temperatures&nbsp;
in the surrounding highlands,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:46.080 --> 00:07:52.960
the first clouds already start forming on the&nbsp;
horizon, ensuring that the cycle will continue.&nbsp;

00:07:52.960 --> 00:07:58.720
Taking a step back, the wild animals are not the&nbsp;
only ones living in, and having their life defined&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:58.720 --> 00:08:04.320
by mother nature's unforgiving cycle. The Pantanal&nbsp;
is also Brazil’s primary region for cattle&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:04.320 --> 00:08:11.600
pastures, with enormous ranches called Fazendas&nbsp;
covering nearly 80% of the basin. The roughly 1.5&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:11.600 --> 00:08:18.080
million people and 4 million cattle have adopted&nbsp;
a lifestyle in sync with the flood pulses, so the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:18.080 --> 00:08:23.680
ranches are run like nowhere else in the world.
Pantaneiros, the term used for cattle ranchers&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:23.680 --> 00:08:29.520
in the Pantanal have immaculate knowledge of which&nbsp;
areas flood first and last, where the best grazing&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:29.520 --> 00:08:34.560
grounds are, and where the safest corridors are&nbsp;
to facilitate the seasonal transhumance ranching&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:34.560 --> 00:08:40.880
style, which involves constantly moving herds&nbsp;
around to access optimal grazing grounds. Fazendas&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:40.880 --> 00:08:45.465
typically include high and lowlands, and can&nbsp;
span thousands of hectares.

00:08:45.465 --> 00:08:48.320
During&nbsp;the wet season, basic utilities often become a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:48.320 --> 00:08:53.840
luxury, with even the major roads becoming&nbsp;
inaccessible, and electricity supply being&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:53.840 --> 00:08:59.520
based on generators and solar systems instead of&nbsp;
a unified grid. Every aspect of infrastructure&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:59.520 --> 00:09:04.560
is built to be in harmony with the natural cycle&nbsp;
and to withstand the floodings as well as possible&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:04.560 --> 00:09:10.320
but economic pressures to industrialize the whole&nbsp;
process are putting the fragile ecosystem at risk.&nbsp;

00:09:10.320 --> 00:09:16.320
Upstream dam proposals for the Paraguay river&nbsp;
threaten to throw off the balance, while paved and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:16.320 --> 00:09:22.720
reinforced roads and flood control measures may&nbsp;
fracture the ecosystem, potentially deteriorating&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:22.720 --> 00:09:28.640
the invaluable biodiversity of the Pantanal.
The effort to balance people's livelihood and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:28.640 --> 00:09:34.400
prosperity against ecological conservation is&nbsp;
a tight rope to walk on, but progress is being&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:34.400 --> 00:09:41.360
made on both ends. In the year 2000, the Pantanal&nbsp;
was recognized as a UNESCO World Heritage Site,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:41.360 --> 00:09:46.240
and extensive national parks and wildlife&nbsp;
reserves were established across the whole basin,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:46.240 --> 00:09:50.800
which in combination with the promotion of&nbsp;
sustainable farming and ranching practices&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:50.800 --> 00:09:56.160
paves the way for many more generations to&nbsp;
enjoy this magnificent nature spectacle.&nbsp;

00:09:56.160 --> 00:10:00.640
Next to the Pantanal, the South American&nbsp;
continent has so many more facets to offer,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:00.640 --> 00:10:06.960
like the complexities of the Amazon Rainforest,&nbsp;
Andean heights and the coastal deserts, which all&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:06.960 --> 00:10:11.600
come together in countries like Peru. If you&nbsp;
want another deep dive, I can recommend this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:11.600 --> 00:10:19.040
video next, or watch what youtube thinks is best&nbsp;
for you here. See you in the next one, cheers.

